	<article>

		<header>
										
			<h1>Small pelagics: a strategic resource for Africa</h1>

			
			<h4>
												12 March 2011
										</h4>

						<h2>An interview with El Hadj Dao Gaye on the occasion of the World Social Forum in Dakar</h2>
					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div class="">		
<div class="embed-image">
<img border="0" src="/var/agritrade/storage/images/el-hadj-dao-gaye_medium/433340-1-eng-GB/El-Hadj-Dao-Gaye_medium_medium.jpg" width="92" height="148"></div></div><p>A fisherman for more than 40 years, El Hadj Dao Gaye represents the entire fisheries sector on the Senegal Economic and Social Council. At the World Social Forum, held in Dakar in February 2011, he was one of the initiators of a workshop to discuss the contribution of fisheries, in particular the small pelagics fishery, to food security in Africa.</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p><b>Q: A few months ago, the United Nations General Assembly agreed on a proposal, initiated by the EU and supported by the African states, to study the state of exploitation of fish stocks at the base of the food chain, such as small pelagics. Have these stocks now acquired a particular importance?</b></p><p>In the context of the current economic crisis facing the African countries, small pelagics have acquired a strategic importance. Sardinellas in particular provide low-price protein to the most disadvantaged groups of the population. Small pelagics truly act as a 'food-safety net'.</p><p>In the case of West Africa, which I know well, it is mostly the catches from small-scale fisheries that provide small pelagics for processing and for the regional trade of smoked, salted or dried fish, although in some countries, such as Ghana or Nigeria, it is the catches of European industrial fishing vessels that supply a significant part of the local market.</p><p>Concerning the small-scale fisheries for small pelagics, it should also be noted that there is an important division of labour. Given the low level of initial investment, a large number of people are involved in the exploitation of small pelagics, from the fisherman to the woman fish processor to the fishmonger, for whom small pelagics provide a livelihood. From this point of view too – in terms of creating jobs for people who have few alternative sources of employment – the exploitation of small pelagics is a strategic issue for African countries.</p><p><b>Q: Small pelagics are migratory stocks, and thus shared by several countries. How is this dimension taken into account in their exploitation?</b></p><p>Personally, I can give you the example of the fisheries agreement between Senegal and Mauritania which, for many years, has allowed a Senegalese fleet to obtain almost 300 fishing licences for small pelagics in Mauritanian waters.</p><p>In parallel with these government-to-government negotiations, since 2008, Senegal and Mauritania professionals have developed a partnership to promote sustainable artisanal exploitation of small pelagics. The role of professionals, recognised by our respective governments, is to facilitate the negotiations, the implementation and the monitoring of the fishing-agreement protocols between the two countries. These efforts have led to the establishment of a professional joint committee which regularly reports on the implementation of the agreement, on aspects such as compulsory landings and marketing, and discusses potential improvements. Improvements are needed for developing local economic activity, which means having appropriate landing infrastructures, enabling the fishing sector to maintain the value of their products, to transport them faster to their final markets, which are sometimes outside Mauritania, and also to avoid post-harvest losses.</p><p>In any case, the fact that the fishing sector from Mauritania and Senegal is now consulted in the negotiations for the renewal of the successive fishing-agreement protocols is a great step forward.</p><p>We have also identified other situations in the region, as in Guinea, where Senegalese fleets catch small pelagics and where there is a strong demand for small pelagics on the local market. Based on our experience of the fishing agreement between Senegal and Mauritania, we could imagine such agreements with other countries, and to respond to the concerns of both Senegalese fishers and Guinean consumers.</p><p>In the long run, I think our countries should move towards agreements not only for regulating access of one country’s fleets to the resources of another country, but also to develop in a concerted manner these fisheries, taking into account environmental aspects in order to prevent the over-exploitation of resources, but also considering aspects regarding supply to local and regional markets.</p><p><b>Q: Cooperation for sustainable fisheries development, between coastal countries and fishing countries is also at the centre of the EU-ACP fisheries partnerships, including partnerships with Mauritania and Morocco, which allows the operation of fleets fishing for small pelagics. What are your views on these small pelagics partnerships?</b></p><p>The industrialised countries’ fleets which exploit small pelagics in the region are almost all composed of the same type of boats: big freezer trawlers – some over 120 metres long.</p><p>European trawlers fishing for small pelagics in Mauritania are making significant by-catch, including sharks and rays, sea turtles, and large quantities of demersal fish. It really is an aspect to be taken into account if we want to talk with the EU about partnership for sustainable fisheries.</p><p>But more generally, what we need is to have a clear idea of who is fishing in our waters and what quantities they are catching, to make sure that this will not lead to over-exploitation of the small pelagics resource. And it’s not only the EU which is fishing there, but also other countries such as China and Russia.</p><p><b>Q: Do you think that there is a lack of information about the quantities of small pelagics caught?</b></p><p>You know, sometimes, there is even no clear information about who is fishing. A few months ago, for example, five Russian factory ships were seen by Senegalese fishermen fishing for small pelagics off the coast of Senegal.</p><p>Senegalese professionals, both the industrial sector from the GAIPES and the artisanal sector from the CONIPAS, sounded the alarm bell about these vessels which are prohibited by Senegalese legislation, and had been allocated licences irregularly. The denouncement by the fisheries sector contributed to solving the problem.</p><p>In Mauritania in recent months, several large factory trawlers from China have also started fishing for fishmeal.</p><p>Even at the level of small-scale fishing, catches are probably underestimated, which can make people think that there is a greater surplus that can be caught by foreign fleets compared to what exists in reality.</p><p>Thus, the West African fishing sector as a whole is concerned about the current levels of exploitation of small pelagics. What we need today is the application of clear limits on catches of small pelagics, and also the application of clear access conditions. I already mentioned the problems of by-catch existing with foreign factory trawlers – if our goal is to promote sustainable fisheries we could for example give priority access to those who use more selective fishing gears.</p><p>It seems to me also, because of the vital importance of small pelagics for food security, that we should not treat fishing that is intended for human consumption in the same way as fishing intended to make fishmeal for fish farms, especially when there may be competition between these two types of fisheries operations.</p><p><b>Q: But isn’t the production of fishmeal for aquaculture in Africa, an important prerequisite for the development of local aquaculture, being promoted by organisations such as NEPAD, the FAO, etc?</b></p><p>I agree, today there is a need to develop aquaculture, above all with a perspective of securing the feeding of African populations. In many African countries, we have natural conditions that are assets for the development of aquaculture: a large number of water bodies such as lakes, rivers, etc. We also have agricultural and fisheries by-products that could serve as food for farmed fish: fish waste, rice bran, peanut meal, etc</p><p>That being said, it is not a solution to develop aquaculture based on the exploitation of wild stocks of small pelagics, that already show signs of overexploitation and which, themselves, are crucial in safeguarding food security.</p><p>This is even more true if we consider that it takes on average 4kg of wild fish, reduced to fish meal, to make 1kg of farmed fish. It would be a mistake to proceed in this way.</p><p>What we need is to base aquaculture on species that do not require feed based on wild fish, an aquaculture which responds to local and regional markets demands, and not one that is based on the unsustainable exploitation of our stocks of small pelagics.</p>
		
		
		
		
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

					
